      "content": "If the nitrogen is being depleted, it's likely due to a nemesis of gardeners everywhere: the pesky potato beetle. But I'm not talking about those insects! In this case, it's probably the tomato hornworm or another insect that's eating away at the plant's leaves. To replenish nitrogen, you can add a balanced fertilizer, such as a 10-10-10 NPK (nitrogen-phosphorus-potassium) formula, to the soil. However, to prevent future depletions, consider incorporating nitrogen-rich organic matter like compost or well-rotted manure into the soil. These will provide a steady supply of nutrients for your plants to grow strong and healthy.",
